Title: The Shack Official Trailer #1 (2017) Sam Worthington, Octavia Spencer Drama Movie HD
Comment: Even though I can't emphasize I still feel like I experienced something similar. I had friends and family members ask me to leave behind my imagination. My imagination to me is like my child. I love her because she was my escape. I have prayed some of my deepest of prayers in my fantasy. I am a writer and an artist. I have imaginary friends. When people demanded that I leave her behind I felt like my child died. I questioned my purpose in life. Before I became suicidal I felt the presence of God enter my mind. It was very different from my imaginary characters and I knew it was God. Who can mistaken Gods presence? He said "I have everything in control." Even though my experience is different I still experienced God and to me that is what matters. I am alive today because God cared enough to put importance on our place of prayer even though it is in my imaginary world.

But I know I have. Some time I wish its as easy to write a letter to god. But if it where that easy. Then the question of life wouldn't be so complicated. We know we all think we focuses on god. We all reminds ourself and love ones. "We love god". But putting my foot out in the working world as my 1st truly honest business man. Starting from his humble start. In trailer and truck. With his last money he went back to construction. A busy humble small success. "I realized". I've forgotten about god. This long road path. With every step of the way some how I felt he is with me. All this I tell me self each time I see a penny on my road path. Reminding my self two word..."thank god for walking with me".  For tomorrow that meal for my family might be gone.

For the next 16 years with my wife. Some how we never starve. We manage to make day by day. With little improve each year. The rodeo was complicated and strive thought extreme complication. But who house is beautiful?

I look on FB, instagrame, every one house is beautiful happy like a dream. The wonderful 1000 friends or followers, The amazing party and event, the beautiful girlfriend, that crazy drugs life. That sexy outfit, forcing our eyes on the color, fabrics of life on medias. But I have forget to thank god. 

It's take months of busy working. Focusing on the next step in life. It come down to one movie today that help me stop. And write this journal. "The shack"...the movies help me truly understand who god is. Thank you

Comment:
I hope that this could be a good sincere faith-based movie.  I fear it will get to "preachy" and want to tie things up in a pretty little bow. Life doesn't, has never, and will never work that way. Faith, logic, spirituality, religion, whatever one personally holds to in order to get through the joys and pains of life is a common thread that all humans share. THAT is what could make this movie truly uplifting, rather than so much schlock designed to appease a target audience. I have no problem with a movie that might have a certain take on religion or spirituality. For example "What Dreams May Come". I'm not enough of a cinephile to give other international examples, though I'm sure there are many. Those perspectives are fine.  Just like any movie, it's how the story is told.
Maybe I'm being too optimistic.

Title: The Shack Official Trailer #1 (2017) Sam Worthington, Octavia Spencer Drama Movie HD
Comment:
So, I know this trailer had a hard time displaying the main plot points, therefore I will do so:

The Shack is based off of one of my most favorite novels of all time. It is about a man whose daughter was kidnapped, raped, and murdered in a small shack in the mountains. Months after, this man receives a letter from "God", inviting him back to the Shack. 
There, he meets the trinity that is God. specifically, the black lady is God the father, the Asian is the Holy Spirit, and the man is Jesus. 
It was a very touching story, and novel. But I do question its veracity as a film. Still, I know I'll see it, if only for my respect of the book.

Title: The Shack Official Trailer #1 (2017) Sam Worthington, Octavia Spencer Drama Movie HD
Comment: Did not know this movie was coming - glad to see it!! Years ago, the book was extremely controversial in the Christian world - in fact friends and fellowships split harshly over it. Most of the haters couldn't get over a black woman representing a big part of God's nature and wisdom - they considered it 100% heresy - and many could not bear to finish reading the short book. But what I took from the book was totally different. The book dealt squarely with an "all too often" theme that the church is unable to successfully confront - and that is how is it possible to find/keep/return to "faith" in the midst of a terrible human tragedy (of the worst kind). This book takes on an event that would shatter the strongest faith, the kind of event that will always force the question "how a good God could possibly exist in such a mean, disgusting, terrible world."  A brave book. If the movie is 90% as good as the book, it will be an incredible flick.

Comment:
This movie had so much potential. I was getting vibes of "Prisoners" from the first part of this trailer... A hard hitting, gritty reality driven story of pain and a bond between a man and his daughter... Then it went all fun time fantasy like something plucked straight out of a family Disney movie and it died from there on. 

Be one type of movie or the other, don't try to splice the two. I appreciate that it's based on the book so this is the direction it follows but it could have remained true and gritty, his delusions didn't need to be so colourful and romanticised they could have gone dark, really dark the kind of darkness you would expect of a man's mind losing his daughter... Not a heartwarming fairy tale.

Comment:
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~ SPOILER WARNING ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

Christians don't like this film

now that may not be a surprise to anyone familiar with 'The Shack', but for those who aren't: the reason Christians reject this story is because the nice black lady 'Elousia', the middle-eastern man, and the asian woman 'Sarayu' are representations of the three persons of the Holy Trinity - God the Father, God the Son and God the Holy Spirit, respectively

of course some people reading this might say; "i'm a christian, i think the shack is a beautiful interpretation of whom God is and how God wants us to live" but i'm afraid they aren't really christians - because anyone who relies on this story to help them understand God, is rejecting the words of Scripture where God constantly refers to Himself in masculine pronouns and reveals Himself as Father

Jesus himself is recorded as speaking of both God the Father and God the Holy Spirit with masculine pronouns

perhaps you don't think this is a big deal, but God also reveals Himself in scripture as being very particular about how mankind represents Him - and we get the word 'Blasphemy' from the idea of giving a witness account in a court of law; and if one gives a false testimony in court, they are 'speaking evil' or 'blaspheming'

and since God goes out of His way in Scripture to refer to Himself in masculine terms, then to represent Him in any other way is a misrepresentation, a false account, or a 'blasphemy'

so bearing in mind that the underlying premise to this whole story is a misrepresentation of whom God is, we then have to ask if the lessons this story teaches 'also' misrepresent what God demands of mankind?

the consensus of real christians is that yes, it does - and anyone who embraces the false god represented in The Shack is still on their way to Hell

Comment: I'm not on the same page with god right now and while I was still going to church and my friend suggested this book, I was hesitant. I ended up reading the whole thing because I LOVE how the writer described god. It's not just a man. He appears to you in the form or person you needs most at the moment and the main character needed a strong female to comfort him. Not a man telling him. That's what I loved most and I don't know if I will ever be so close to God, but I know that if I need him, he will come to me in the way he thinks is best.
